Sig Eps suspended until April '97

Second fraternity
to face sanctions
this year

By Mark Gordon
Editor in Chief

A Pitt fraternity, already on suspen-
sion by its national office for hazing,
was put on probation for over a year by
the university. .

Sigma Phi Epsilon was suspended
until April 1997 for violating Pitt’s anti-
hazing policy. The fraternity said it will
appeal the decision.

“We’re particularly concerned when
a hazing violation such as this one
involves alcohol connected with
minors,” said Dennis Donham, assistant
vice chancellor for student affairs. '

Donham sent a letter detailing the sus-
pension to Sigma Phi Epsilon president

‘ Jeff Black yesterday. In the letter,

Donham stated that the hazing incident

» “occurred with the advice and consent of

the pledge educator, who should be the
official fraternity monitor to prevent this
type of activity.”

Donham also stated in the letter that
he was concerned “that at least one indi-
vidual appears to have been restrained”
during the incident which occurred on
Nov. 29. ,

The fraternity’s appeal will be heard

by Vice Chancellor for Student and
Public Affairs Leon Haley.

“We are disappointed by the decision
of the university in light of our coopera-
tion with the investigation,”. Black said.
He declined further comment, not wanti-
ng to jeopardize the appeal. .

Donham said that the fraternity was
“very forthcoming in the investigation,
and this was the -first time Pitt has had
any problems with the group.”

But he also said, “It clearly was a haz-
ing violation.” _

Last month, Sigma Phi Epsilon’s
national office in Richmond, Va., sus-
pended the fraternity indefinitely for its
role in the hazing incident. The suspen-

sion banned alcohol at mixers.

