The problem with all of this external
noise, and the gen-
eral need for stimu-
lation from the out-
side, is that there is
very little time left
for personal reﬂec-
tion. When you can
spend time in cre-
ative solitude, you
can get in touch
with what you think
is important in life,
how you want to spend your time and
what contributions you want to make to
the world as your life progresses.

Being alone, in itself, is not enough. It
is using the solitude for some of these
self-exploratory activities that really
enriches your life. If you want to test

 

this out, begin setting aside some quiet
time each week and use this time to
think about what you want your life to
be like (apart from the wants of your
parents or your
peers). Begin to
write your thoughts
about these things
in a journal fre-
quently to see how
your ideas begin to
deepen and diversi-
fy as you gain
more experience
with self-analysis.
You might also
begin to pay attention to your dreams.
Write them down when you remember

them, and think about what theymight

mean. Also, write down things that you
have enjoyed in the past but haven’t
done much recently. List other things
that you have always wanted to do but

have never had the courage to try. Don’t
try to restrict these thoughts or wishes to
what you presently think is attainable.
As long as they remain in your con-
sciousness, there is still a chance that
they can happen. Remember that every-
thing we accomplish in our lives hap-
pens at least twice — once in our minds
and once in reality. We need to think
things and dream things before we can
make them happen.

The important message in all of this is
that to create a rich and meaningful life
for ourselves we need to take time for
self-analysis and reflection. lt’s not easy
to do, because we are pulled in so many
different directions. However, if we can
include creative solitude in our lives, our
understanding of ourselves and of others
will grow, and our lives will be richer
for the effort.

