Opinions

Icky politician cooties

It’s started. If you don’t want to get hit by any stray pieces
of mud ﬂying around, you better go underground for the next
seven months. That's right! It’s political campaign time now,
and the name-calling is about to get into full swing.

We’ve been privy to a few minor glimpses of the campaign
circus already, and if they are any indication of what is to
come, it’s going to get ugly. Bill Clinton has begun his attack
against the Republican party as a whole, ridiculing its unwill-
ingness to compromise on the budget, its position on social
reformsand everything else the 104th Congress has done.

Unfortunately for the Republicans, the mud-slinging will
come from two sides for anyone going for the Republican
nomination. Since Clinton is running unopposed, the primary
elections are going to turn into a Republican bloodbath over
who will challenge the presidentin November. This leaves
Clinton with plenty of time to run a campaign against the

entire Republican party during the primaries and then wipe‘

up the floor with whomever is left in November.

Actually, Clinton’s job is not that difficult right now, since
he only has to sit back and watch the Republican candidates
tear each other apart over the next few months." Apparently
no one has told the Republicans that it may be more impor-
tant to get your party elected than to get yourself elected. So
the Republicans will dredge up every piece of dirt they can
find on each other and plaster it before the media, giving
Clinton all the help he needs.

Not to exclude Clinton from the mudslinging, you can be
assured that he will join i.n with both hands once the pri-

' maries are over and the Republicans pretend to like each

other again. Then we’ll also be bombarded with anti-Clinton
propaganda from the Republican candidate, which he will be
forced to sling back in kind.

Speaking of the media, you can expect to hear the mud ﬂy
everywhere youturn. Televisions are plastered, radios are
one giant sound bite for six-or-so months and don’t be sur-
prised if you turn up some propaganda on the Internet. With
technology advancing so quickly, you can bet it won’t take
the politicians long to discover cyber—mud. ‘

If over the next few months, you find yourself ready to
crawl into the storm cellar, don’t worry. You are not alone.
Political campaigning, from both parties, has b_ecome a game
of who can say what about whom the greatest number of
times. If you pay close attention, you’ll notice that you will
rarely hear what any one candidate does or believes, only
what his or her opponent didn’t do or doesn’t believe.

So how about some real issues, please? We are, after all,

adults, aren’t we? Second grade was a long time ago, and,’

we’re voting for president of the United States —- not Cootie
King. '

